In .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` overrides. Instead, use the **Window lifecycle events** via `CreateWindow` or the `Window.Created`, `Window.Stopped`, `Window.Resumed` events.

**Option 1 — Override in your `App` class:**

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2 — Subclass `Window`:**

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated() { /* OnStart */ }
    protected override void OnStopped() { /* OnSleep */ }
    protected override void OnResumed() { /* OnResume */ }
}
```

Then return `new MyWindow(new MainPage())` from `CreateWindow`.

**Key difference:** MAUI's lifecycle is per-window (supporting multi-window on iPad/desktop), whereas Xamarin.Forms was per-application.
